Recent climate change has highlighted how variable plant phenology is when observed over time and space across different species \citep{Yu2010,Vitasse2013,Rudolf2019}, with many studies documenting how quickly phenology can shift with warming \citep{Fitter2002,Menzel2006}. But experiments conducted under controlled environments have shown that it is possible to consistently define early to late phenology from the known underlying cues \citep{Chuine1999,Harrington2015,Flynn2018}. This work has found early species to generally require only small amounts of forcing (\R{em1}\color{red}accumulated warm temperatures usually in the spring\color{black}), chilling (\R{em2}\color{red}cool temperatures usually accumulated in the fall and winter\color{black}), and shorter photoperiod to leaf out. \R{R2_cueSizea}\color{red}Thus under experimental conditions, we observe relatively small responses to each of these cues. In contrast, later species have larger responses to chilling and/or longer photoperiods, and larger forcing responses to experimental cues \citep{Laube2014,Flynn2018}\R{R2_cueSizeb}\color{black}. The consistency of these relationships allows us to estimate early to later active species across plant communities and diverse species assemblages.  \\ 

